It is good, for journalists, to ask Sam Bankman-Fried where all the money w=
ent, but he is not going to tell you. The possibilities are:
=09He knows where the money went, and he has huge incentives to lie about i=
t, or=09He doesn=E2=80=99t know where the money went, as he sort of keeps s=
aying, and he will just pass along his confusion to you.

There is not some third possibility where you can sit Bankman-Fried down an=
d he will be like =E2=80=9Chere is a detailed timeline of all the innocent =
mistakes we made and how much customer money=C2=A0each one vaporized.=E2=80=
=9D If he had those details available to him, he would not have vaporized t=
he money. Or he would have, but the mistakes were not innocent, and he will=
 not describe them accurately. Either way,=C2=A0you will not get a satisfyi=
ng explanation, from him.
The person who will tell you=C2=A0where the money went at Bankman-Fried=E2=
=80=99s crypto exchange, FTX, and its affiliated trading firm, Alameda Rese=
arch, is John Ray, six months from now. Ray is the current chief executive =
officer of FTX, appointed moments before it filed for bankruptcy, and the f=
ormer bankruptcy wrangler of disasters like Enron. He   harrumphed into ban=
kruptcy court last month to be like =E2=80=9Cthis is the biggest mess I=E2=
=80=99ve ever seen, and I=E2=80=99ve seen Enron,=E2=80=9D and if I were him=
 I=E2=80=99d say that constantly=C2=A0to my kids. Ray=E2=80=99s=C2=A0well-p=
aid and frankly very interesting=C2=A0job is to sort it out, and I assume e=
ventually he will. That sorting apparently involves, like, Googling news ar=
ticles to see what venture capital investments FTX made, because FTX did no=
t itself keep a list of its own investments. That is what we are dealing wi=
th here.=C2=A0=C2=A0
But Ray is=C2=A0methodically piecing together the accounts, not giving inte=
rviews, and keeping his complaints to court filings. Meanwhile Bankman-Frie=
d is at loose ends in his Bahamas penthouse and seems to be spending his ti=
me calling up journalists and compulsively confessing to =E2=80=A6=C2=A0wha=
tever it is he thinks he is confessing to? =E2=80=9CI didn=E2=80=99t ever t=
ry to commit fraud on anyone,=E2=80=9D he   told Andrew Ross Sorkin yesterd=
ay, but, otherwise.
Here are the  video and  transcript of Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s interview wi=
th Sorkin at the DealBook conference yesterday. Here is an  interview with =
Jen Wieczner in New York magazine, which was published today though conduct=
ed on Nov. 17. Here is an interview with  George Stephanopoulos on =E2=80=
=9CGood Morning America=E2=80=9D.=C2=A0
I want to give a stylized version of Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s account of wha=
t went wrong at FTX and Alameda. It goes something like this:
=09FTX International was a crypto exchange for sophisticated margin traders=
.
  [1]
=C2=A0A =E2=80=9Ccrypto exchange=E2=80=9D is both an exchange =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0a place where people can meet to buy and sell crypto =E2=80=94=C2=A0but =
also a broker-dealer, a firm that holds its customers=E2=80=99 crypto for t=
hem and gives them financing.=09Everyone trading on FTX was basically borro=
wing money from FTX to put on leveraged crypto trades, or lending out the c=
rypto in their FTX accounts to earn interest, or both. This=C2=A0necessaril=
y=C2=A0means that the customers=E2=80=99 crypto was not segregated: If you=
=E2=80=99re lending out your crypto to earn interest, or borrowing crypto t=
o make bigger trades, you can=E2=80=99t expect your crypto to all sit in a =
segregated account doing nothing. If you are trading via leveraged perpetua=
l futures, a big FTX product, you certainly can=E2=80=99t expect your crypt=
o to all be sitting there waiting for you: You don=E2=80=99t own=C2=A0any c=
rypto; you just have a derivative trade with FTX.=09One very important trad=
er on FTX was Alameda Research, which had huge leveraged positions on FTX.=
=09Alameda=E2=80=99s position was overcollateralized, but FTX had a little =
bit of an $8 billion accounting boo-boo, so it thought Alameda=E2=80=99s po=
sition was less leveraged than it actually was.=09Then there was a huge sud=
den correlated drop in the prices of crypto assets, which left Alameda unde=
rcollateralized, and FTX =E2=80=94=C2=A0due to the accounting boo-boo =E2=
=80=94 was surprised to find out how undercollateralized it was.=09Other tr=
aders noticed this and withdrew money from FTX, creating a =E2=80=9Crun on =
the bank.=E2=80=9D=09The run on the bank also led to further declines in th=
e prices of crypto assets, particularly the ones that Alameda held, leaving=
 FTX without enough collateral to pay out all of its customers.

Something like that.=C2=A0There are a lot of problems with that story, it o=
mits some damning details, and I don=E2=80=99t think that it entirely makes=
 sense on its own terms. But never mind that. Let=E2=80=99s just take=C2=A0=
Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s story. Mostly I want to emphasize how different it =
is from=C2=A0the story that Bankman-Fried and FTX and Alameda were telling =
as of even a month ago.
Most obviously, the stuff about customer deposits being rehypothecated make=
s sense, at some level, on its own, and I have   told some version of it my=
self. FTX was an exchange that was especially welcoming to leveraged trader=
s, its customers were there to borrow and lend crypto, so of course it used=
 every part of the customer deposits. But that's not what it said! When the=
 =E2=80=9Crun on the bank=E2=80=9D started, Bankman-Fried tweeted (and then=
 deleted) =E2=80=9CFTX has enough to cover all client holdings. We don=E2=
=80=99t invest client assets (even in treasuries).=E2=80=9D I can sit here =
and say =E2=80=9Cwell it was an exchange for leveraged traders, of course e=
veryone=E2=80=99s assets were being rehypothecated, they can=E2=80=99t real=
ly have expected otherwise.=E2=80=9D But FTX was lying about it to the cust=
omers!=C2=A0
Or everyone who interviews Bankman-Fried points to the bit of the FTX terms=
 of service saying that they won=E2=80=99t do that. From the Sorkin intervi=
ew:

SORKIN:=C2=A0=E2=80=A6 It says, =E2=80=9CNone of the digital assets in your=
 account are the property of, or shall or may be loaned to, FTX Trading. FT=
X Trading does not represent or treat digital assets in users=E2=80=99 acco=
unts as belonging to FTX Trading.=E2=80=9D So, how is it possible that Alam=
