oney to FTX. And so I think in the meantime, some of them were wiring money=
 to Alameda Research to get credited on FTX. And I think that was a substan=
tial sum. And I think that the FTX=E2=80=99s internal accounting did correc=
tly, effectively try to debit Alameda for those funds. But it didn=E2=80=99=
t happen in the primary account. And so it didn=E2=80=99t happen =E2=80=94 =
it created a discrepancy between the display of the account and what was re=
ally going on there. I=E2=80=99m still looking into exactly how that worked=
 mechanically, but that did make that position size substantially larger th=
an I thought and, I think, than what you would=E2=80=99ve gotten from both =
the normal avenues.=E2=80=9D I do not know what to say about the accounting=
 boo-boo except that, like, =E2=80=9Cwe asked customers to send money to ou=
r hedge fund because our exchange didn=E2=80=99t have a bank account, and t=
hen we lost track of it=E2=80=9D is not *obviously* better than just saying=
 =E2=80=9Coh that money, we stole it.=E2=80=9D


  [3] I mean, it=E2=80=99s the main thing in Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s versio=
n of the story; if the story turns out to be =E2=80=9Cehh we just stole all=
 the money=E2=80=9D then the mechanics of the liquidation engine aren=E2=80=
=99t that important.=20


  [4] At a very high level of generality, is this   Sam Bankman-Fried=E2=80=
=99s box? =E2=80=9CYou can even finance this, right? You put X token in a b=
orrow lending protocol and borrow dollars with it. If you think it's worth =
like less than two thirds of that, you could even just like put some in the=
re, take the dollars out. Never, you know, give the dollars back. You just =
get liquidated eventually. And it is sort of like real monetizable stuff in=
 some senses.=E2=80=9D


