<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Tether lending</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know, man! Here=E2=80=99s a st=
ory:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">There is a crypto shadow bank. People=
 hand over their money or crypto to the shadow bank, which they trust for w=
hatever reason.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The shadow bank ta=
kes the customers=E2=80=99 money or crypto and lends it to other crypto tra=
ding firms.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=E2=80=9CDon=E2=80=99t=
 worry,=E2=80=9D the shadow bank says, =E2=80=9Cwe only lend customers=E2=
=80=99 money to carefully vetted counterparties, and all of our loans are h=
ighly overcollateralized by good liquid collateral.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li sty=
le=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=E2=80=9CWe have very sophisticated risk systems=
,=E2=80=9D it adds, =E2=80=9Cthat make it virtually impossible for us to lo=
se any money on these loans.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5p=
x;">=E2=80=9CWhat? No,=E2=80=9D it adds, =E2=80=9Cyou can=E2=80=99t see the=
 list of counterparties or a breakdown of the collateral or the loan-to-val=
ue ratios or the terms of the loans, that is very secret business informati=
on.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Crypto prices drop, i=
t turns out that the shadow bank=E2=80=99s loans were highly concentrated a=
nd not all that well collateralized, and it freezes customer money and goes=
 bankrupt.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This summer, that was the story of Celsius, an=
d Voyager, and eventually BlockFi. Last month, it was the story of FTX. Ver=
y sophisticated risk systems, all of them. Lots of liquid collateral.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In other news <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/29860385.273543/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2=
xlcy9yaXNpbmctdGV0aGVyLWxvYW5zLWFkZC1yaXNrLXRvLXN0YWJsZWNvaW4tY3J5cHRvLXdvc=
mxkLTExNjY5ODc1NTkwP21vZD1ocF9sZWFkX3BvczQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfb3ffd5=
2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> here is the Wall Street Journal today</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The company behind the tether stablecoin has i=
ncreasingly been lending its own coins to customers rather than selling the=
m for hard currency upfront. The shift adds to risks that the company may n=
ot have enough liquid assets to pay redemptions in a crisis.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Tether Holdings Ltd. says it lends only to eli=
gible customers and requires that borrowers post lots of =E2=80=9Cextremely=
 liquid=E2=80=9D collateral, which could be sold for dollars if borrowers d=
efault.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These loans have appeared for several quarters=
 in the financial reports that Tether shows on its website. In the most rec=
ent report, they reached $6.1 billion as of Sept. 30, or 9% of the company=
=E2=80=99s total assets. They were $4.1 billion, or 5% of total assets, at =
the end of 2021.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Tether calls them =E2=80=9Csecured loans=E2=80=
=9D and discloses little about the borrowers or the collateral accepted. Al=
ex Welch, a Tether spokeswoman, confirmed that all of the secured loans lis=
ted in the reports were issued and denominated in tether. The company said =
the loans were short-term and that Tether holds the collateral.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Tether, which is incorporated in the British V=
irgin Islands, doesn=E2=80=99t publish audited financial statements or a co=
mplete balance sheet, leaving outsiders with an incomplete picture of the c=
ompany=E2=80=99s financial health. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CEligible clients are borrowing USDT,=
=E2=80=9D Ms. Welch said, using an abbreviation for tether. =E2=80=9CLoans =
are overcollateralized by extremely liquid assets that Tether=E2=80=99s pru=
dent risk management admits as collateral.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I=E2=80=99m sure there <em>are</em> crypto sha=
dow banks who only lend at low loan-to-value ratios against extremely liqui=
d assets and have prudent risk management! I keep finding myself writing ab=
out the other ones.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The thing about Celsius, Voyager and BlockFi =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0and to an extent FTX =E2=80=94=C2=A0is that=C2=A0<em>of cour=
se=C2=A0</em>they were lending out their customers=E2=80=99 money. That was=
 the business they were in; if you are parking your crypto at a crypto shad=
ow bank and getting 8% interest, it=E2=80=99s because the shadow bank is do=
ing something (something risky!) with your crypto to earn that 8% (plus its=
 own profits). The thing with Tether is that there=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29860385.273543/aHR0cHM6Ly9jb2lu=
bWFya2V0Y2FwLmNvbS9jdXJyZW5jaWVzL3RldGhlci8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB01f9af=
8d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> like $65 billion outstanding</a>, it pays no interest and one=
-month US Treasury bills yield like 3.8%. People do not give Tether money i=
n order to earn interest on it; they give Tether money in order to get back=
 USDT to use for crypto transactions. If you were Tether, you could just pa=
rk their money in the safest and most liquid possible investments and earn =
billions of dollars of revenue that you get to keep. This is a very good an=
d easy business. You don=E2=80=99t need to do anything else. When people ca=
ll you up for loans, instead of evaluating their collateral and creditworth=
iness and negotiating good documentation and having a prudent risk manageme=
nt and monitoring system, you could just say =E2=80=9Cno we=E2=80=99re good=
=E2=80=9D and buy Treasuries and sleep well on your giant pile of money.</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And that is, as far as I know,=C2=A0<em>mostly=
=C2=A0</em>what Tether does; <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/29860385.273543/aHR0cHM6Ly90ZXRoZXIudG8vZW4vdHJhbnNwYXJlbmN5LyNy=
ZXBvcnRz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0d15f7fa" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> it reports</a> that ab=
out 58% of its assets are in US Treasury bills. But 9% are in secured loans=
, and those secured loans apparently take the form=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>o=
f =E2=80=9Cpeople give Tether dollars for USDT, and Tether lends those doll=
ars to businesses secured by collateral=E2=80=9D but rather =E2=80=9Cpeople=
 borrow USDT directly from Tether by posting cryptocurrency collateral.=E2=
=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ever since Tether has existed, there have been=
 pretty vocal Tether skeptics. In the early days the main form of skepticis=
m was that Tether was not really backed one for one by dollars, that Tether=
 was doing something weird with its dollars. This seems to have been=C2=A0<=
em>mostly=C2=A0</em>untrue =E2=80=94=C2=A0most of the dollars were there mo=
st of the time =E2=80=94=C2=A0though also definitely=C2=A0<em>a bit=C2=A0</=
em>true; in the past, Tether definitely <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/29860385.273543/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vc=
GluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDQtMjYvdGhpbmdzLWdvdC13ZWlyZC1mb3Itc3RhYmxlY29p=
bi10ZXRoZXI_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTIwMTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1=
fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMjAxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dW=
Zm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe5915534" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  shipped some of its money o=
ut to its affiliated crypto exchange</a> for dodgy reasons. And even today =
Tether makes a lot of noise about how transparent it is without actually be=
ing transparent; it publishes attestations of its assets and liabilities th=
at fall frustratingly short of being audited balance sheets. Still it seems=
 reasonably likely that, these days, Tether=E2=80=99s money is mostly where=
 it says it is, and where it says it is is mostly in Treasury bills and oth=
er pretty safe stuff.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Instead, the main form that <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29860385.273543/aHR0cHM6Ly9jcnlwdG8t=
YW5vbnltb3VzLTIwMjEubWVkaXVtLmNvbS90aGUtYml0LXNob3J0LWluc2lkZS1jcnlwdG9zLWR=
vb21zZGF5LW1hY2hpbmUtZjhkY2Y3OGE2NGQz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe81b75af" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;"> Tether skepticism takes these days</a> is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I am not su=
re I can entirely capture it, but the basic flavor of it is:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The price of Bitcoin (of crypto genera=
lly, etc.) seems to be set by an exchange rate between dollars and Bitcoins=
. People have dollars and use them to buy Bitcoins, which makes the price o=
f Bitcoin go up. Or people trade their Bitcoins for dollars, etc.</li>=09<l=
i style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">But really the demand for Bitcoin is largel=
y people trading=C2=A0<em>USDT=C2=A0</em>for Bitcoin.=C2=A0<em>Tether=C2=A0=
</em>is the instrument that sets the price of Bitcoin.</li>=09<li style=3D"=
margin-bottom: 5px;">That seems fine if you think of Tether as =E2=80=9Cpeo=
ple put dollars into a box and get back an equal number of USDT that are fu=
lly backed by those dollars.=E2=80=9D Then a USDT is just a more crypto-con=
venient form of a dollar.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">But real=
ly =E2=80=94=C2=A0the skeptics say =E2=80=94=C2=A0Tethers are printed out o=
f thin air in order to keep up the price of Bitcoin.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This theory of course=C2=A0<em>converges=C2=A0=
</em>with =E2=80=9CTethers are not fully backed by dollars,=E2=80=9D but it=
s emphasis is different, not =E2=80=9CTether got the dollars and misplaced =
them=E2=80=9D but rather =E2=80=9CTether is a form of fractional reserve ba=
nking in which Tethers are created by buying Bitcoin instead of the reverse=
.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I do not propose to evaluate this theory furth=
er except to say: Doesn=E2=80=99t that Journal story sound a bit like that?=
 I mean here is a story you could tell:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You have 1,000 Bitcoin worth about $1=
7 million.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You want to buy more Bi=
tcoin, but you do not have any dollars.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: =
5px;">You go to Tether and say =E2=80=9Chey give me 17 million USDT, in exc=
hange I=E2=80=99ll put up 2,000 Bitcoins as collateral.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li=
 style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Tether is like =E2=80=9Csure that=E2=80=99s =
the business we=E2=80=99re in=E2=80=9D and hands you 17 million USDT.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You use that 17 million USDT =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0notionally worth $17 million =E2=80=94=C2=A0to buy 1,000 more Bitcoin=
.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Now you have 2,000 Bitcoin.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You post the 2,000 Bitcoin as collater=
al to Tether for the loan, which is now overcollateralized with liquid coll=
ateral ($34 million worth of Bitcoin).</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5=
px;">More USDT have been created to buy Bitcoin, but no new dollars have co=
me into the system.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Maybe this is fine, no problem, just margin le=
nding.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000=
000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bot=
tom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color:=
 transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a> But if your concern is =E2=80=9CTethers are printed out of thin air in=
 order to allow people to buy crypto without putting any actual dollars in,=
=E2=80=9D then this might make you nervous.=C2=A0</p>
